            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1571050291,
            "creation_date": 1571049807,
            "body": "<p>Why don't you use the built-in <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/lang/Integer.html#parseInt(java.lang.String,%20int)\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Integer#parseInt(s, radix)<\/a> method: <\/p>\n\n<pre><code>Integer.parseInt(\"001010\", 2)\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p><code>2<\/code> is the radix (base) for the number here telling that it's a binary (base-2) number. It will automatically convert <code>001010<\/code> binary number to <code>10<\/code> decimal value.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 58375102,
            "question_id": 58374901,
            "last_edit_date": 1571050291
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/mxQgb.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 5303869,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 4232523,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/4232523/hadi-moloodi",
                "reputation": 639,
                "display_name": "Hadi Moloodi"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1571050528,
            "creation_date": 1571050528,
            "body": "<p>If you really want to do this recursively on your own you can do it this way.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>static int BinaryNum(String n, int p) {\n    if (n.length() == 1) {\n        return (int) (Integer.parseInt(n) * Math.pow(2, p));\n    } else {\n        return (int) ((n.charAt(n.length() - 1) - 48) * Math.pow(2, p)) + BinaryNum(n.substring(0, n.length() - 1), p + 1);\n    }\n}\n\n  public static void main(String[] args) {\n        System.out.println(BinaryNum(\"101010\", 0));\n    }\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
